üìñ English Grammar Guide

Comprehensive grammar topics from A1 to B2 levels with English & Urdu explanations

1. Present Simple Tense (Muzare)

English: Used for habits, routines, facts, and general truths.

Urdu: Aadat, rozana ke kaam, aur aam haqaiq ke liye istemal hota hai.

Structure: Subject + Verb (base form) / Verb+s (for he/she/it)

‚úÖ I work every day. (Main roz kaam karta hoon)

‚úÖ She works at a bank. (Woh bank mein kaam karti hai)

‚úÖ The sun rises in the east. (Suraj mashriq se nikalta hai)

‚ùå He work ‚Üí ‚úÖ He works

2. Present Continuous Tense (Muzare Jari)

English: Used for actions happening right now or around now.

Urdu: Abhi ho rahay kaam ya is waqt ke qareeb ho rahay kaam.

Structure: Subject + am/is/are + Verb-ing

‚úÖ I am studying now. (Main abhi parh raha hoon)

‚úÖ She is working today. (Woh aaj kaam kar rahi hai)

‚úÖ They are playing cricket. (Woh cricket khel rahay hain)

3. Past Simple Tense (Mazi)

English: Used for completed actions in the past.

Urdu: Mazi mein mukammal honay wale kaam ke liye.

Structure: Subject + Verb-ed / Irregular verb form

‚úÖ I worked yesterday. (Main kal kaam kiya)

‚úÖ He went to school. (Woh school gaya)

‚úÖ She bought a new phone. (Us ne naya phone kharida)

4. Future Simple (Will) - Mustaqbil

English: Used for future actions, predictions, and promises.

Urdu: Aanay walay kaam, peshgoiyan, aur waday ke liye.

Structure: Subject + will + Verb (base form)

‚úÖ I will call you tomorrow. (Main tumhein kal call karun ga)

‚úÖ It will rain today. (Aaj barish hogi)

‚úÖ We will help you. (Hum tumhari madad karein ge)

5. Articles (a, an, the)

English: 'A/an' for non-specific items, 'the' for specific items.

Urdu: 'A/an' aam cheez ke liye, 'the' khaas cheez ke liye.

A: a book, a car (consonant sounds)

An: an apple, an hour (vowel sounds)

‚úÖ I saw a cat. (Ek billi dekhi)

‚úÖ The cat was black. (Woh billi kaali thi)

6. Pronouns (Zameer)

English: Words used instead of nouns.

Urdu: Naam ki jagah istemal honay wale lafz.

Subject: I, you, he, she, it, we, they

Object: me, you, him, her, it, us, them

‚úÖ I love my family. (Main apni family se pyar karta hoon)

‚úÖ Give him the book. (Usko kitaab do)

7. Prepositions (Harf-e-Jar)

English: Words showing position, time, or direction.

Urdu: Maqam, waqt, ya rukh dikhane wale alfaz.

‚úÖ The book is on the table. (Kitaab mez par hai)

‚úÖ I live in Houston. (Main Houston mein rehta hoon)

‚úÖ I wake up at 6am. (Main 6 baje uthta hoon)

8. Question Formation (Sawal)

English: Use question words or auxiliary verbs.

Urdu: Sawal ke alfaz ya helping verbs se sawal bantay hain.

‚úÖ Do you like tea? (Kya tumhe chai pasand hai?)

‚úÖ What is your name? (Tumhara naam kya hai?)

‚úÖ Where do you live? (Tum kahan rehtay ho?)

9. Adjectives (Sifat)

English: Words that describe nouns.

Urdu: Ism ki khasoosiyat batane wale lafz.

‚úÖ A beautiful girl. (Ek khubsurat larki)

‚úÖ The car is fast. (Gari tez hai)

‚úÖ A nice big red car. (Ek achhi bari laal gari)

10. Adverbs (Zarf)

English: Words that describe verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.

Urdu: Fail ki khasoosiyat batane wale lafz.

‚úÖ He runs quickly. (Woh tezi se daurta hai)

‚úÖ I always brush my teeth. (Main hamesha daant saaf karta hoon)

11. Comparatives & Superlatives

English: Used to compare things.

Urdu: Cheezon ki tulna karne ke liye.

‚úÖ This book is cheaper than that one. (Ye kitaab us se sasti hai)

‚úÖ He is the tallest boy. (Woh sab se lamba larka hai)

12. Modal Verbs (Can, Should, Must)

English: Express ability, permission, advice, or obligation.

Urdu: Qabiliyat, ijazat, mashwara, ya lazmi kaam.

‚úÖ I can swim. (Main tair sakta hoon)

‚úÖ You should study. (Tumhe parhna chahiye)

‚úÖ I must go. (Mujhe jana hi hai)

13. Conditionals (Agar... To...)

English: If-sentences showing conditions and results.

Urdu: Shart aur nateeja dikhane wale jumle.

‚úÖ If you heat water, it boils. (Agar paani garam karo, to ubalta hai)

‚úÖ If it rains, I will stay home. (Agar barish hui, to main ghar rahun ga)

14. Passive Voice (Majhool)

English: When the action is more important than who does it.

Urdu: Jab kaam ka fail maloom na ho ya ahmiyat na ho.

‚úÖ English is spoken here. (Yahan English boli jati hai)

‚úÖ The car was stolen. (Gari churai gayi)

15. Present Perfect Tense

English: For actions that started in past and affect the present.

Urdu: Mazi se shuru aur abhi tak mausar kaam.

‚úÖ I have lived here for 5 years. (Main yahan 5 saal se reh raha hoon)

‚úÖ She has finished her work. (Us ne apna kaam khatam kar liya hai)

16. Countable vs Uncountable Nouns

English: Nouns you can/cannot count individually.

Urdu: Aise ism jo gin sakte hain ya nahin gin sakte.

Countable: I have three books. (Mere paas teen kitabein hain)

Uncountable: I need some water. (Mujhe thora paani chahiye)

17. Conjunctions (Raabt)

English: Words that connect sentences.

Urdu: Jumlon ko jorhnay wale alfaz.

‚úÖ I like tea and coffee. (Mujhe chai aur coffee pasand hai)

‚úÖ He is smart but lazy. (Woh hoshyar hai lekin aalsi hai)

18. Possessive Forms (Milkiyat)

English: Show ownership or relationships.

Urdu: Milkiyat ya rishta zahir karne ke liye.

‚úÖ Ali's book (Ali ki kitaab)

‚úÖ The students' books (Talaaba ki kitabein)

19. Gerunds & Infinitives

English: Verb forms used as nouns.

Urdu: Fail ko ism ki tarah istemal karna.

‚úÖ Swimming is fun. (Tairna maza hai)

‚úÖ I want to eat. (Main khana chahta hoon)

20. There is / There are

English: To say something exists.

Urdu: Kisi cheez ke wujood ke baray mein batana.

‚úÖ There is a book on the table. (Mez par ek kitaab hai)

‚úÖ There are three books. (Teen kitabein hain)

üá¨üáß British English (UK)

Pronunciation Differences:

‚Ä¢ Water = "waw-tuh" (not "wah-der")

‚Ä¢ Schedule = "shed-yool" (not "sked-yool")

‚Ä¢ Tomato = "tuh-mah-toe" (not "tuh-may-toe")

‚Ä¢ Bath = "bahth" with long 'a' sound

Common Phrases:

‚Ä¢ Cheers! = Thanks / Goodbye (Shukriya / Alvida)

‚Ä¢ Brilliant! = Great / Excellent (Zabardast!)

‚Ä¢ Fancy a cuppa? = Want some tea? (Chai piye ge?)

‚Ä¢ Proper = Very, really (Bohat)

‚Ä¢ Mate = Friend (Dost)

YouTube Channels:

‚Ä¢ BBC Learning English

‚Ä¢ English with Lucy

‚Ä¢ Papa English

üá∫üá∏ American English (USA)

Pronunciation Differences:

‚Ä¢ Water = "wah-der" (with 'd' sound)

‚Ä¢ Schedule = "sked-yool"

‚Ä¢ Tomato = "tuh-may-toe"

‚Ä¢ Can't = "kant" (short 'a' sound)

Common Phrases:

‚Ä¢ What's up? = How are you? (Kya haal hai?)

‚Ä¢ Awesome! = Great (Zabardast!)

‚Ä¢ You bet! = Of course (Bilkul!)

‚Ä¢ For real? = Really? (Sach mein?)

‚Ä¢ Dude = Friend / Guy (Yaar)

YouTube Channels:

‚Ä¢ Rachel's English

‚Ä¢ Go Natural English

‚Ä¢ Learn English with TV Series
